         <ce:floats>
            <ce:figure id="fig1">
               <ce:label>Figure 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0010">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0010" view="all">Logic Block Diagram of the Theory Section</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0015" view="all">For the ARCC of WBGSs, (1) semiconductor physicists and (2) materials scientists use different theories with different terms. Semiconductor physicists use energy band theory with terms like “acceptor” and “hole,” whereas materials scientists use ionic crystal localized states electronic theory. We try to combine both theories and put forward a novel idea to achieve ARCC of WBGSs, that is, to first realize ALI to achieve H-CM and H-TSCC and then, by taking precise control of the CCCE of materials, finally achieving ARCC.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr1" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr1" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig2">
               <ce:label>Figure 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0015">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0020" view="all">Scheme of the ZnO Lattice in the Absence of a Cation (Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup>) and an Anion (O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup>)</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0025" view="all">The left side shows a lack of a Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup>. Because Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> is small in size, and O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> is bound by other Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup>, O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> can be basically maintained in the original lattice position, which exhibits a high thermal stability. Meanwhile, in comparison with the strict periodic structure, the absence of Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> will cause only a small change to neighboring atoms. The energy band theory tells us that this slight deformation will not create a carrier scattering center with large cross-section. Thus, ZnO with trace of Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> absence possesses high carrier mobility similar to that of integrity lattice.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0030" view="all">The right side shows a lack of an O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup>. Because O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> has a large radius, its absence will lead to large lattice distortion and even collapse. Such a lattice structure is thermally unstable. Also, in comparison with the strict periodic structure, there is a carrier scattering center with large cross-section, finally decreasing substantially the carrier mobility.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0035" view="all">Obviously, there is a positive correlation between high thermal stability and high carrier mobility, and both of these depend on ALI.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr2" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr2" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig3">
               <ce:label>Figure 3</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0020">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0040" view="all">Schemes of the Mechanism of p-Type Conduction with Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> in the Lattice, Explained by the Energy Band Theory and the Ionic Crystal Localized States Electronic Theory</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0045" view="all">(A) From the perspective of energy band theory, as Li only has one valence electron, the valence band cannot be filled up. Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> can receive electrons and create a shallow acceptor level, thus achieving p-type conduction.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0050" view="all">(B and C) From the perspective of ionic crystal localized states electronic theory, (B) is the image of unexcited acceptor, and (C) is the acceptor excitation and hole migration process. When the trace of Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> is replaced by Li<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup>, according to electrical neutrality, the four oxygens coordinated by Li<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup> must be one O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> and three O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup>. It is obvious that the unexcited acceptor is LiO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">6−</ce:sup>. When the unstable O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> captures the electron of other O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> (LiO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">6−</ce:sup> + O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> → LiO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">7−</ce:sup> + O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup>), the acceptor changes from LiO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">6−</ce:sup> and LiO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">7−</ce:sup> and is excited. The new O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> can also capture the electron of O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> nearby, and thus it seems that O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> migrates freely in the lattice, which is the so-called hole. (In fact, O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> corresponds to a positive charge center in the O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> ocean.)</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr3" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr3" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig4">
               <ce:label>Figure 4</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0025">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0055" view="all">Schemes of ZnO:Li to Illustrate that ZnO with Different Conduction Types Has Different CCCEs</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0060" view="all">(A) One Li replaces a Zn. Its CCCE is <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>. The energy band theory shows that Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> is an acceptor, thus making the material possess p-type conduction.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0065" view="all">(B) One Li fills in the interstitial site in the lattice. Its CCCE is (ZnO)<mml:math altimg="si3.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>Li</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>. The energy band theory shows that Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf> is a donor, thus making the material own n-type conduction.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0070" view="all">An important point is that we are discussing micro-doping of semiconductors with the carrier concentration of 10<ce:sup loc="post">14</ce:sup>–10<ce:sup loc="post">19</ce:sup> cm<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup>, and the value of <mml:math altimg="si2.gif">
                        <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                     </mml:math> is 10<ce:sup loc="post">−8</ce:sup>–10<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup>.<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0245" refid="bib10">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">10</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref>
                  </ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr4" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr4" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig5">
               <ce:label>Figure 5</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0030">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0075" view="all">Schemes of ZnO:Li to Illustrate that CCCE Uniquely Determines Conduction Type</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0080" view="all">(A and B) In (A), one Li replaces a Zn. Its CCCE is <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>. Shown in (B) is the energy band diagram of (A), which creates a shallow acceptor level, Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> level. At room temperature, the electron in valence band is easily excited to this level, so this kind of ZnO:Li is a good p-type conduction material with high hole concentration.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0085" view="all">(C and D) In (C), one Li fills in the interstitial site, accompanied by a V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>. Its CCCE is the same as that of (A). Shown in (D) is the energy band diagram of (C). V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> is an acceptor with two electrons, while Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf> is a donor that can provide an electron. When V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> and Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf> coexist, the electron of Li will automatically fill in the lowest level of V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>, and this eventually forms a net deep level acceptor (2.8 eV). The material is still p-type conductive and its net acceptor concentration is the same as that of (A), but at room temperature its carrier concentration is quite low, performing as a nonconductive insulator.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0090" view="all">Note that the net acceptor concentration can be uniquely determined through CCCE, which depends on the value of <mml:math altimg="si2.gif">
                        <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                     </mml:math>, but the depth of energy level cannot be confirmed only with CCCE.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr5" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr5" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig6">
               <ce:label>Figure 6</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0035">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0095" view="all">Schemes of One Permanent Thermodynamic Process to Fabricate p-ZnO</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0100" view="all">(A) An expected p-ZnO with the CCCE of <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, whose typical characteristic is one Li-substituting Zn in the lattice. From the perspective of crystallography, the electronic configuration of one of four O coordinated by Li<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup> is 2p<ce:sup loc="post">5</ce:sup>.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0105" view="all">(B) An unstable ZnO with the CCCE of <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> without the “boundary condition” of ALI, which was produced in strong oxidizing atmosphere in one permanent thermodynamic process. In this extreme condition, one residual O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> will be squeezed into the interstitial sites, which results in large lattice distortion and totally destroys ALI. The produced p-ZnO is quite unstable.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0110" view="all">(C) An unexpected i-ZnO with the CCCE of <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> in one permanent thermodynamic process. Because one Li substitutes Zn, another residual Li has to be filled in the interstitial sites in the lattice. All oxygen ions are exhibited as O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup>. (From the perspective of energy band theory, the electrons offered by Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf> donor will automatically fill into the shallow level formed by Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>. As a result, in this material, the concentration of acceptor and donor are equal.)</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr6" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr6" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig7">
               <ce:label>Figure 7</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0040">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0115" view="all">Scheme of the Multi-Step Thermodynamic Process to Fabricate p-ZnO</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0120" view="all">Step 1 is to produce an integrated oxygen lattice with trace of V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> in a strong oxidizing atmosphere. Theoretically, in order to prevent Vo as much as possible, <mml:math altimg="si9.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mtext>μ</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">&gt;</mml:mo>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mtext>μ</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> should be satisfied, where <mml:math altimg="si10.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mtext>μ</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> remains constant and <mml:math altimg="si11.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mtext>μ</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> is related to the oxygen partial pressure (<mml:math altimg="si12.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mtext>μ</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                           <mml:msubsup>
                              <mml:mtext>μ</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                          <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mn>0</mml:mn>
                           </mml:msubsup>
                           <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">+</mml:mo>
                           <mml:mtext>RTln</mml:mtext>
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo>[</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo>]</mml:mo>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>). To increase <mml:math altimg="si11.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mtext>μ</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, strong oxidizing atmosphere must be adopted. On the other hand, metal Zn has a high vapor pressure (about 63 Pa at 700°C), and <mml:math altimg="si13.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mtext>μ</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mtext>Zn</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">&gt;</mml:mo>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mtext>μ</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mtext>Zn</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>vapor</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> is usually satisfied when gas concentration of Zn is quite small. So, under high temperature and strong oxygen pressure, it is easy to evaporate Zn from the crystal lattice to create V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>. However, these conditions are difficult to implement with the existing equipment being unable to conduct. In addition, the product of this step is a p-type semiconductor with deep acceptor energy levels (apparently an insulator).</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0125" view="all">Step 2 is to introduce Li atoms into ZnO lattice to change V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> into Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> in a reductive Li or CH<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>Li atmosphere. An intuitive idea is introducing Li through the vapor, as Li also has high vapor pressure (about 6 Pa at 700°C), which makes it easy to evaporate solid Li into vapor. Because the radius of Li is small, once Li-vapor meets ZnO with trace of V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>, it will migrate to V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> in the anionic integrated lattice and become Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>. To react sufficiently, the excessive Li must be introduced, so it is inevitable that the extra Li will fill in the interstitial sites and become Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf>, whose concentration is even more than that of Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> in the lattice. Therefore, in this step the product we gain is an n-type semiconductor with a net donor concentration. In addition, Li can also be introduced by means of electrochemistry.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0130" view="all">Step 3 is to anneal in a vacuum or weak oxidizing atmosphere at low temperature to “kick” the relatively unstable Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf> out of lattice while keeping Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> stable. The anionic lattice can be kept dynamically stable under low temperature and weak oxidizing atmosphere. In this process, once the concentration of Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf> is less than that of Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> in the lattice, the net shallow acceptor level can be formed, and thereby p-ZnO with H-CM and H-TSCC can be fabricated.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0135" view="all">Finally, we have to point out that this method is implemented with the intrinsic thermodynamic characteristics of ZnO. The fabricating processes depend on the specific characteristics of the dopant and the matrix. For example, both Li and Zn have high vapor pressure and small radius and can travel through the oxygen crystal lattice easily. However, for other materials these characteristics are not always satisfied. The particular regulation of ALI and CCCE should be designed on the basis of materials' specific characteristics.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr7" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr7" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig8">
               <ce:label>Figure 8</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0045">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0140" view="all">Schemes of the Self-Developed Equipment for the Three-Step Thermodynamic Process, and the Photoluminescence Spectra Result and Lattice Structure for Each Treatment Step</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0145" view="all">(A–C) Section scheme of the annealing furnace, which is mainly made of double steel shells (A). When it works, the cooling water circularly flows between steel shells to make the temperature less than 150°C at the inner shell, especially at the sealing ring. There is a small platinum-resistance-wire heating device in the center of the cavity, which can heat up to 1,300°C. Such equipment can anneal ZnO single crystals at 70 atm and 1,300°C. The photoluminescence (PL) spectra (B) and the corresponding lattice structure (C) of ZnO single crystals after step-1 annealing treatment for 24 h. The signal of V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> (at 2.4 eV) is quite strong.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0150" view="all">(D–F) Section scheme of the electrochemical reactor in which Li is doped in ZnO crystals at room temperature (D). It is a discharge battery with ZnO single crystals as cathode and metal Li as anode. The electrochemical process is that Li<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup> is diffused into the ZnO lattice from the upper LiPF<ce:inf loc="post">6</ce:inf> electrolyte, and the electrons come from the below electrodes contacted with ZnO. It can be described as an electrode reaction equation, Li<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup> + V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> + e<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup>→Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>. A current controller should be introduced to make the reaction proceed smoothly and keep the “boundary condition” of ALI as well. The PL spectra (E) and the corresponding lattice structure (F) of ZnO single crystals after the electrochemical process. The signal of V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> is observed to have disappeared, which means that the reaction has proceeded successfully.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0155" view="all">(G–I) Section scheme of the annealing furnace to anneal ZnO in NO atmosphere (G). The PL spectra (H) and the corresponding lattice structure (I) of ZnO single crystals after step-3 treatment at 200°C. The signal of V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> has reappeared, which indicates that this thermodynamic condition is not entirely suitable for single crystals. More detailed thermodynamic regulation should be carried out. However, via this process, high-resistance ZnO can be fabricated repeatedly.<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0250" refid="bib11">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">11</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref>
                  </ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr8" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr8" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig9">
               <ce:label>Figure 9</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0050">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0160" view="all">Schemes of Multi-Step Thermodynamic Process to Fabricate p-ZnO Thin Films and the Quality Characterization Results</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0165" view="all">(A) Three-step thermodynamic process to fabricate p-ZnO thin films that epitaxially grow on Ga-doped ZnO substrates.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0170" view="all">(B and C) The <ce:italic>I-V</ce:italic> characteristic curve of LED devices based on the fabricated p-ZnO thin film, which shows the rectification property of p-n junction (B). The threshold voltage is near 3.4 V and the device begins to shine at 4 V. The inset is a diagram of the LED structure. Photograph of the LED device and its electroluminescence (C).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr9" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr9" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig10">
               <ce:label>Figure 10</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0055">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0175" view="all">Two Methods of Fabricating p-GaN with the CCCE of <mml:math altimg="si7.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>GaN</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>MgN</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>
                  </ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0180" view="all">(A) One permanent thermodynamic process. The result is that it always tends to form the thermodynamically stable CCCE, <mml:math altimg="si6.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>GaN</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>Mg</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>3</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>N</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>. The residual Mg can only fill in the interstitial sites under the “boundary condition” of ALI.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0185" view="all">(B) Multi-step thermodynamic process we present. Step 1 is doping Mg directly in Li-rich atmosphere under a particular thermodynamic condition, before adjusting the thermodynamic condition to control the large-radius Mg to become Mg<ce:inf loc="post">Ga</ce:inf> and the small-radius Li to become Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf>. Step 2 is to “kick out” the pre-filled Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf> in another thermodynamic condition and finally fabricate the expected p-GaN.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr10" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/gr10" xlink:type="simple"/>
            </ce:figure>
         </ce:floats>
