            <ce:abstract id="abs0010" view="all" class="author"><ce:abstract-sec id="abssec0010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="abspara0010" view="all">The arbitrary regulation of carrier concentration (ARCC) for wide-band-gap semiconductors (WBGSs) has been a research challenge for many years. Here, for the fabrication of high-quality WBGSs materials, we propose a theoretical knowledge base that can be understood by both semiconductor physicists and materials scientists; specifically, chemical composition complete expression (CCCE) uniquely determines the conduction type of materials. Under this guidance, we present a fabricating strategy comprising a multi-step thermodynamic process specifically to achieve ARCC using our effort with p-ZnO as an example. The knowledge and strategy described here are of universal meaning, showing great potential for the fabrication of other WBGSs and a new perspective for transforming insulators to semiconductors.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            <ce:abstract class="graphical" id="abs0015" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sectitle0015">Graphical Abstract</ce:section-title>
               <ce:abstract-sec id="abssec0015" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="abspara0015" view="all">
                     <ce:display>
                        <ce:figure id="undfig1">
                           <ce:link locator="fx1" xlink:href="pii:S2590238520301156/fx1" xlink:type="simple"/>
                        </ce:figure>
                     </ce:display>
                  </ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec>
            </ce:abstract>
            <ce:abstract class="editor-highlights" id="abs0020" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sectitle0020">Progress and Potential</ce:section-title>
               <ce:abstract-sec id="abssec0020" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="abspara0020" view="all">Wide-band-gap semiconductors (WBGSs), due to their special structure (of wide band gap), can be applied to UV light emission, high voltage resistance, high radiation resistance, and other fields with extreme conditions. However, how to achieve arbitrary regulation of these materials' carrier concentration has been a bottleneck hindering relevant development for many years.</ce:simple-para>
                  <ce:simple-para id="abspara0025" view="all">Based on our 15-year effort on ZnO, we present a stereoscopic theory and a strategy to fabricate expected WBGSs, which could change the traditional paradigm of WBGS fabrication and produce materials genuinely usable in practice. The theory and strategy are universal, and enabling their application to the fabrication of other WBGS such as Ga<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>, GaN, and AlN is our further plan. Being a significant theoretical guide to the development of WBGS, they will bring great benefit to WBGS fabrication and application, such as the aspects of deep UV detection and radiation detection. Furthermore, they could be available to other materials to achieve the arbitrary regulation of carrier concentration and to further transform more insulators into semiconductors. They can inspire tremendous innovation in many fields.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec>
            </ce:abstract>
            <ce:abstract class="teaser" id="abs0025" view="all">
               <ce:abstract-sec id="abssec0025" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="abspara0030" view="all">We propose a new theory called “chemical composition complete expression” and a multi-step thermodynamic process of wide-band-gap semiconductor fabrication, for which our p-ZnO research is taken as an example. The theory and strategy provide a novel perspective and paradigm for expected high-quality wide-band-gap semiconductor fabrication and could even help to transform more insulators to semiconductors.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec>
            </ce:abstract>
