         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec1" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0030">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0010" view="all">For most researchers, metals, semiconductors, and insulators are three concepts that represent different materials with the typical corresponding carrier concentrations being &gt;10<ce:sup loc="post">22</ce:sup>, 10<ce:sup loc="post">14</ce:sup>–10<ce:sup loc="post">19</ce:sup>, and &lt;10<ce:sup loc="post">12</ce:sup> cm<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup>, respectively. Such a classification is more naturally acceptable to most researchers but could actually lead to some misunderstandings of the true nature. According to the solid band theory, developed directly from quantum mechanics, insulators and semiconductors partake of completely equivalent electronic band structures. All materials with filled band structures (FBS) are semiconductors, whereas those with half-filled band structures are metals. In other words, if challenging the basic rule of quantum mechanics is not our choice, we have to recognize that, under the approximate hypothesis of singleelectron, materials with ordered crystalline structure are in either metal or semiconductor state without an independent insulator state.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0015" view="all">In fact, it is the integrated development of quantum mechanics that declares that all traditional insulators are semiconductors. Theoretically, through proper doping,<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0040" refid="bib1">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">1</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref> functional semiconductors with a carrier concentration of 10<ce:sup loc="post">14</ce:sup>–10<ce:sup loc="post">19</ce:sup> cm<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup> transformed from any traditional insulators might be “cooked” out. However, the development of semiconductor selected a different approach. After 20 years of major work on Ge, Si, and GaAs, attempts to transform other insulators into semiconductors then became a nonmainstream research topic for a much longer time, from 1970 to 2000. Therefore, for the public only Ge, Si, and GaAs (and perhaps InP) were regarded as semiconductors, whereas other traditional insulators were still “insulators.” This developing story actually implies a hidden prerequisite of successful transformation of insulators into semiconductors (TIS), that is, whether the arbitrary regulation of carrier concentration (ARCC)<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0045" refid="bib2">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref> can be easily achieved. Si,<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0050" refid="bib3">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref> Ge, and GaAs have this intrinsic characteristic of ARCC, which finally makes them occupy most applications in electronic engineering to become the symbol of the Information Age. After 2000, researchers renewed the attention of TIS in some “insulators” termed WBGSs, such as GaN, SiC, ZnO, and Ga<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>, to meet the demand of some advanced applications such as UV emission and high-voltage devices.<ce:cross-ref id="crosref5055" refid="bib4">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">4</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref> In contrast, although today there is more precision control equipment for researchers than in the 1950s,<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0055" refid="bib5">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">5</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref> the complete ARCC in any WBGSs still cannot be achieved after 30 years of hard work.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0020" view="all">The dilemma above could be attributed to the absence of full knowledge sharing between semiconductor physicists and materials scientists. The energy band theory only tells us what kind of extended-state electronic structure we finally need. However, the “building blocks” of solids are independent atoms or ions, whose electrons are described to be in a localized state. To frame a hypotyposis, semiconductor physicists are like designers who know exactly what function the integrated architectures are expected to carry out, whereas materials scientists are architects who understand the “building blocks” but without comprehension of integrated effects. The lack of common academic terminology between them leads to the failure of building ideal architectures with ARCC.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0025" view="all">Based on this situation, here we provide a "stereoscopic" perspective and some common academic terms that can be understood by both semiconductor physicists and materials scientists. This originates from our 15 years of work in ZnO single crystal<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0060" refid="bib6">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">6</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">,</ce:sup>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0065" refid="bib7">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">7</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref> and its carrier concentration regulation, which can be described as follows. For a compound semiconductor, its conduction type is uniquely determined by its chemical composition complete expression (CCCE). The detailed microscopic structure of doping and occupation will not affect the material's carrier type when the CCCE has been confined.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">Although in this length-limited paper there is not enough space to verify the whole theory, we will use our specific research and thinking on p-ZnO to illustrate it. First we will describe the theory in detail and present an important “boundary condition” on the fabrication of WBGSs. Through specific thermodynamic analysis, we propose that the multi-step thermodynamic process is indispensable to fabricate a high-quality WBGS. Our equipment and process designed to achieve multi-step thermodynamics in p-ZnO fabrication will be illustrated. To illustrate the universality of this multi-step thermodynamic process, we also provide our conjecture on the fabrication of GaN with high hole concentration in the same spirit.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">The significance of our investigation is that it declares the intrinsic connection among the carrier concentration, the CCCE, and the thermodynamic state in the material manufacturing process. It uses the language of materials scientists, CCCE, to describe the concept to semiconductor physicists. Through this theory, we encourage researchers to pay more attention to the CCCE instead of the microscopic specific occupation and vacancy, which are usually uncontrollable in the normal semiconductor fabricating process. As novel knowledge, this builds a bridge between energy band theory and localized states electronic theory with important common academic terms. It points out the concrete description (ions and ion clusters) of the abstract concept in energy band theory, such as “hole” and “acceptor.” Obviously, this knowledge changes the paradigm of semiconductor fabrication, and its universal nature determines that other WBGSs can also benefit from this theory. The development and flexible use of this theory could even achieve our final dream of achieving TIS in many more materials as mentioned in our topic.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec2" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0035">Theory</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">In this section, we describe that a high-quality semiconductor, while realizing ARCC, must also possess high carrier mobility (H-CM) and high thermal stability of carrier concentration (H-TSCC). The latter two both strongly depend on anionic lattice integrity (ALI). By using ZnO as an example, the origin of matter's conductivity from the perspective of energy band theory and ionic crystal localized states electronic theory will then be explained. The combination of these two perspectives can even help to find the corresponding “building blocks” of the abstract concept in energy band theory, the hole. Finally, combining the former two insights, we further explain how CCCE determines conduction types in ZnO with the “boundary condition” of ALI. Under precise control of CCCE, we can uniquely determine the net concentration of acceptor or donor and thus gain the expected conduction type. Combing the thermodynamic analysis in the next section, if acceptor and donor can be tuned to shallow ones by selecting proper thermal routes, ARCC can be achieved. The logic block diagram is shown in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0070" refid="fig1">Figure 1</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="fig1"/>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.1" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0040">Basic Requirements for a High-Quality Semiconductor</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">As mentioned above, a semiconductor material must possess a “dominant gene” that makes ARCC easily achievable. Besides this, a high-quality semiconductor should also possess two mutually coupled “recessive genes,” i.e., the doped material still has high carrier mobility (H-CM) and high thermal stability of carrier concentration (H-TSCC). For traditional semiconductors Si, Ge, and GaAs, when ARCC can be achieved by a correct selection of doping elements, H-CM and H-TSCC seem to be satisfied automatically. However, things are different for WBGSs, because H-CM and H-TSCC seemingly cannot be satisfied directly. The 30 years of hard work mentioned above, based on the traditional paradigm to make ARCC the first consideration, have not succeeded in fabricating WBGSs with H-CM and H-TSCC. Therefore, we suggest giving up the traditional paradigm of achieving ARCC first, and make H-CM and H-TSCC the first concerns instead. A brand-new fabricating strategy will then be on the horizon.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">Analysis of TSCC and CM makes us pay more attention to lattice thermal stability, because the latter will affect the former two directly. In traditional practice, lattice thermal stability is the business of materials scientists. We will take ZnO, a typical ionic compound, as an example. From the perspective of materials science,<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0075" refid="bib8">
                           <ce:sup loc="post">8</ce:sup>
                        </ce:cross-ref> larger-radius anions (O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup>) constitute the lattice skeleton, even though they have smaller mass. On the contrary, greater-mass cations (Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup>) with smaller radius contribute less to the skeleton but act as “binders” filled in the anionic lattice interstitial sites (tetrahedral center, octahedral center, and so on) (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0080" refid="fig2">Figure 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig2"/>). The lattice of ionic compounds can be analogous to the following structure: a skeleton of “balloons” (O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup>) is glued by small “wooden balls” (Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup>), located in the interstitial sites. The intuitive geometry tells us that the absence of small amounts of “wooden balls” still can keep the whole skeleton stable with little distortion, whereas the absence of “balloons” will lead to a larger distortion and even collapse of skeleton. In summary, lattice thermal stability depends on ALI.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">Moreover, TSCC obviously has a direct relationship with lattice thermal stability and thus also depends on ALI. The unstable lattice will create uncontrollable defects and lead naturally to the change of carrier concentration.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">A little more description is needed here to briefly describe how H-CM also depends on ALI.<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0085" refid="bib9">
                           <ce:sup loc="post">9</ce:sup>
                        </ce:cross-ref> According to energy band theory, we can deduce that H-CM originates from a strictly periodic potential field, and any slight departure from periodic structure will decrease mobility exponentially (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0090" refid="fig2">Figure 2</ce:cross-ref>). The discussion above tells us that the absence of small amounts of “wooden balls” has much less effect on periodic potential field, whereas the absence of “balloons” will cause larger lattice distortion or even collapse, which will greatly affect periodic potential field. Therefore, we can conclude that the realization of H-CM also needs to satisfy ALI.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.2" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0045">Conductivity of Semiconductors in Two Perspectives: Energy Band Theory and Ionic Crystal Localized States Electronic Theory</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">The analysis above has told us an important “boundary condition” in the fabrication of ionic compound semiconductors with H-CM and H-TSCC, namely, ALI must be achieved primarily. In this section, we need to suspend that conclusion temporarily and turn to another subject, the conductivity of semiconductors. First, we briefly describe the different understanding of semiconductor conductivity according to energy band theory and ionic crystal localized states electronic theory. We then try to combine those two perspectives and point out the corresponding concrete “building blocks” of hole and acceptor in materials science.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">As is known, energy band theory, the paradigm for describing electronic structures of solids, is the basis of semiconductor physics. Its basic rule can be described as follows: First, all atoms are ionized to bare nuclei and then these nuclei are arranged in a predetermined periodic structure. The formation mechanism of this periodic structure is not an important issue here. The energy bands (electronic state) are formed by linear reorganization of all periodic-arranged atomic orbits. Second, all ionized electrons filled the band structure in order of energy states from low to high. This perspective describes the existing electronic state of materials accurately, with their formation process neglected here but explained by the materials science paradigm. First, all atoms will undergo a chemical reaction and become electron-carrying ions rather than just bare nuclei. Second, the crystal structure will be “assembled” by these ions with different radii and charges. This description is more approximate to the formation process but lacks a correct understanding of the final electronic state. As we can see, electrical properties of materials are determined by the energy band structures formed by nuclear arrangement of periodic structure, whereas the materials are formed by the assembly of electron-carrying ions. Therefore, if we can establish a "stereoscopic" perspective, as we have already mentioned, whereby the typical terms of energy band theory, such as holes and acceptors, can correspond to the “building blocks” (ion clusters and ions) of materials science, this will make it more straightforward to understand semiconductor doping and to fabricate expected semiconductors, especially for WBGSs.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">As mentioned earlier, instead of verifying the theory, we would like to illustrate it with the example of ZnO:Li. The calculation of energy band theory shows us that the energy bands near the Fermi surface in ZnO are chiefly formed by the linear reorganization of the 4s orbits of Zn and the 2p (2s) orbits of O, as shown in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0095" refid="fig3">Figure 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig3"/>A. The main components of the conduction band are the 4s orbits of Zn, and the main components of the valence band are the 2p (2s) orbits of O. For a solid with n Zn atoms and n O atoms, the 8n valence electrons come from the 4s orbits of Zn and the 2p (2s) orbits of O. The rule of conservation of state number tells us that the state number of the valence band is exactly 8n, and thus the intrinsic ZnO is FBS, performing as a nonconductive insulator. When a Zn is replaced by a Li, because the state number of the 2s orbit of Li is exactly the same as that of the 4s orbits of Zn, after state-number-conservation linear reorganization the state number of the valence band is still 8n. However, the whole electrically neutral system only contains 8n − 1 valence electrons and thus the highest state on the valence band cannot be occupied, and the material will achieve p-type conduction. At a glance, it seems that the defects of Li-substitutional Zn (Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>) are acceptors.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">If we change our perspective to ionic crystal localized states electronic theory, chemical reaction takes place firstly to transform Zn atoms and O atoms into Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> and O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup>, and all electrons are tightly bound to these two ions. Because of the lack of free electrons, the whole assembling structure is not conductive. If a Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> is replaced by a Li<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup>, in order to maintain electrical neutrality of the whole material, one of four O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> coordinated by Li<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup> must be transformed into O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0100" refid="fig3">Figure 3</ce:cross-ref>B). Obviously this O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> is very active, and can capture the electron of neighboring O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> coordinated by Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> and change itself to O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup>. In fact, the process here actually corresponds to the excitation of acceptor (hole excitation process in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0105" refid="fig3">Figure 3</ce:cross-ref>C). We know that all O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> in lattice are equivalent except for the four oxygen ions coordinated by Li<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup>. Once one of the O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> coordinated by Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> is transferred into O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup>, it will be very easy for it to capture electrons from any other O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> coordinated by Zn<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> without energy loss. On the macro-level, this kind of process embodies the migration of O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> and net positive charge in the whole lattice (hole migration process in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0110" refid="fig3">Figure 3</ce:cross-ref>C).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">Through this perspective, we can concretize the abstract concept whereby the hole is O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> and the unexcited and excited acceptors are LiO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>
                        <ce:sup loc="post">6−</ce:sup> and LiO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>
                        <ce:sup loc="post">7−</ce:sup>, respectively, as shown in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0115" refid="fig3">Figures 3</ce:cross-ref>B and 3C. This concretization process exactly points out the “building blocks” of acceptors and holes. To fabricate p-ZnO, our aim is to build up a lattice with trace of O<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> (10<ce:sup loc="post">15</ce:sup>–10<ce:sup loc="post">19</ce:sup> cm<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup>) directly. Meanwhile, if this trace element is imparted into chemical expression, we will find that the chemical expression of the whole material is <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (a little Li<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> solid solution in ZnO lattice). In general, the value of <mml:math altimg="si2.gif">
                           <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                        </mml:math> is smaller than 10<ce:sup loc="post">−6</ce:sup>, and such a slight <mml:math altimg="si2.gif">
                           <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                        </mml:math> is always neglected by materials scientists but plays a key role in conduction type! It can be deduced that the chemical expression containing all elements can be an important factor for conduction type. For this reason, we propose CCCE.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.3" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0050">CCCE: A New Concept for Determining Conduction Type</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">We already know that a high-quality compound semiconductor must satisfy ALI, and p-type conduction is equivalent to a trace of Li<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> dissolved in ZnO lattice. We now combine these two conclusions to initiate the final discussion on how CCCE determines conduction types of materials under the “boundary condition” of ALI. First, we would like to give a detailed definition of the CCCE. CCCE is the chemical expression including all elements of the whole system no matter how tiny the content of element, whether it can be observed, or whether it is doped intentionally. Therefore, CCCE is essentially the language of materials science with all components in a system and the carrier type shown intuitively. Here, we also illustrate it with the example of ZnO:Li.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">
                        <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0120" refid="fig4">Figure 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig4"/> illustrates that ZnO with different conduction types will have different CCCEs under the “boundary condition” of ALI. From the perspective of energy band theory, the defects of Li-substituting Zn (Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>) (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0125" refid="fig4">Figure 4</ce:cross-ref>A) are shallow donor-accept levels, making a p-type conduction, whereas interstitial Li (Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf>) (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0130" refid="fig4">Figure 4</ce:cross-ref>B) are shallow donor-defect levels, making an n-type conduction. Evidently, via the perspective of energy band theory, the specific microstructure must be pointed out and the conduction type determined. However, if we turn to CCCE, it can be seen that the CCCE of p-ZnO is <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
