                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0135" refid="fig4">Figure 4</ce:cross-ref>A) whereas that of n-ZnO is (ZnO)<mml:math altimg="si3.gif">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>Li</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0140" refid="fig4">Figure 4</ce:cross-ref>B). Therefore, materials with p-type and n-type conduction hold different CCCEs. In fact we can verify that the converse conclusion that CCCE can uniquely determine conduction types is also correct.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">To further illustrate the above conclusion, in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0145" refid="fig5">Figure 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig5"/>, we show that materials with the same CCCE but different microstructures exhibit the same conduction type. <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0150" refid="fig5">Figures 5</ce:cross-ref>A and 5C have exactly the same CCCE, <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. However, <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0155" refid="fig5">Figure 5</ce:cross-ref>A represents p-ZnO with a shallow acceptor level (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0160" refid="fig5">Figure 5</ce:cross-ref>B) , whereas <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0165" refid="fig5">Figure 5</ce:cross-ref>C represents p-ZnO with a deep acceptor level (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0170" refid="fig5">Figure 5</ce:cross-ref>D). Thus, the net concentration of acceptor or donor is uniquely determined by CCCE. Furthermore, it is seen that by using the concept of CCCE, which is more acceptable or familiar to materials scientists, we can uniquely determine conduction types of materials without distinguishing their specific microstructure, which is the business of semiconductor physicists.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec3" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0055">Thermodynamic Process with Specific Demand</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">In the theory section, we explained that fabricating a high-quality semiconductor should realize the precise regulation of the CCCE under the “boundary condition” of ALI. In general, when fabricating a WBGS, the realization of ALI needs one specific thermodynamic condition which usually cannot meet the aforementioned demand automatically. In fact, to achieve a precise regulation of CCCE and finally realize ARCC in WBGSs, a widely tuned thermodynamic condition could be inevitable. For example, for GaN, sometimes almost completely different thermodynamic conditions are in demand for achieving the carrier concentration of 10<ce:sup loc="post">17</ce:sup> or 10<ce:sup loc="post">19</ce:sup> cm<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup>, unlike the traditional semiconductors such as Si and Ge.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">In view of this fact, we propose that the satisfaction of ALI and CCCE needs subsequent two or more different thermodynamic processes instead of a permanent one. Our strategy can be described as follows: First, achieve ALI under a suitable thermodynamic condition. In this step, the CCCE is not purposefully controlled and thus we cannot obtain the semiconductor with expected carrier concentration. Second, because the whole lattice has been formed, it should have the ability to tolerate certain changes of thermodynamic environment. This dynamic stability of ALI allows us to introduce a widely tuned thermodynamic condition to regulate trace changes of cations in lattice, making the precise control of CCCE possible. In brief, for WBGSs, via the multi-step thermodynamic process we can regulate CCCE with the “boundary condition” of ALI, and semiconductors with desired carrier concentration, H-CM, and H-TSCC will be obtained. Obviously, different WBGSs have their own intrinsic thermodynamic characteristics, so different thermodynamic processes will be applied. However, the spirit of the multi-step thermodynamic process actually permeates all successful fabrications of WBGSs. In this paper, we introduce our strategy of ZnO:Li to illustrate this spirit. First, we will briefly explain why the normal fabricating strategy of p-ZnO (one permanent thermodynamic process) cannot make stable p-ZnO and then show our work in p-ZnO fabrication through the multi-step thermodynamic process.</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.1" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0060">Thermodynamic Analysis: Why Normal Li Doping Cannot Achieve p-Type Conduction</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">As already mentioned, theoretically ZnO with pure Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> doping is a good p-type material with shallow acceptors. <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0175" refid="fig6">Figure 6</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig6"/>A shows that CCCE of this p-ZnO is <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. There is no doubt that it is a high-quality p-type semiconductor we desire. However, this ideal material usually cannot be fabricated in one permanent thermodynamic process, for the following reason. If we choose the fine control of CCCE first, what we actually want is the trace of Li<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> doped in ZnO. It is well known that the formation of Li<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> requires strong oxidizing atmosphere and that the crystal structure of Li<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> is quite different from that of ZnO, which will cause large lattice distortion and the failure to achieve ALI, as shown in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0180" refid="fig6">Figure 6</ce:cross-ref>B. Alternatively, if we choose to achieve ALI first, the product will mostly form i-type. <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0185" refid="fig6">Figure 6</ce:cross-ref>C shows that in the normal thermodynamic process, Li<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O is more stable than Li<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>. Thus, <mml:math altimg="si4.gif">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mtext>Li</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>O</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is a more possible CCCE to be formed than <mml:math altimg="si1.gif">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>LiO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. Under the “boundary condition” of ALI, the extra doping Li has to fill in the interstitial sites. This analysis can well explain that in one permanent thermodynamic process, the doping of Li always results in the equivalent Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> and Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf>, rather than more Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> as we expect. The case of doping other group IA elements is the same as that above. For the doping of group VA elements such as nitrogen, in one permanent thermodynamic process it tends to form the stable CCCE of <mml:math altimg="si5.gif">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>ZnO</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mtext>Zn</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mn>3</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mtext>N</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> which is still i-type. The detailed description is not shown here.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.2" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0065">Our Fabrication Strategy for p-ZnO</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">The multi-step thermodynamic process is illustrated in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0190" refid="fig7">Figure 7</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig7"/>. Step 1 is annealing bulk or thin-film single crystals of ZnO in strong oxidizing atmosphere to create a trace of V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> with the “boundary condition” of ALI. Step 2 is filling V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> with Li by annealing the ZnO single crystals in Li or CH<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>Li-vapor atmosphere or using the electrochemical method to dope Li into ZnO lattice. Step 3 is “kicking” residual Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf> out of the lattice, which is introduced in step 2. It is obvious that the whole purpose of these processes is to control CCCE under the “boundary condition” of ALI. In this way, the strategy of regulating carrier concentration proposed above can be well implemented theoretically, with both ALI and specific CCCE being achieved.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec4" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0070">Equipment Designed for the Demanded Thermodynamic Conditions</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">Obviously, there is no sophisticated semiconductor equipment currently available to achieve the multi-step thermodynamic process we have described. Here, we would like to introduce some of our efforts made during equipment fabrication.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">Step 1 requires a hyperbaric oxygen atmosphere to keep O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> lattice integrity possible. At the same time, to make a trace of Zn cross the potential barrier of O<ce:sup loc="post">2−</ce:sup> lattice, high temperature is required. To achieve that thermodynamic condition, we have developed high-pressure equipment that can seal high-temperature oxygen by metal, as shown in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0195" refid="fig8">Figure 8</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="fig8"/>A. The equipment can anneal the material in 70 atm oxidizing atmosphere at 1,300°C. <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0200" refid="fig8">Figures 8</ce:cross-ref>B and 8C illustrate that we have fabricated ZnO with high-concentration V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> while maintaining ALI.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">The second step of filling V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> with Li can adopt various methods. A typical choice is to anneal ZnO with V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> in Li-vapor atmosphere at 300°C–500°C. However, the shortcoming of this method is the difficulty to prevent Li being oxidized before it arrives at the surface of ZnO. Another method is electrochemistry, through which we can inject Li in ZnO lattice at room temperature (for details see <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0205" refid="fig8">Figures 8</ce:cross-ref>D–8F). It can be described as an electrode reaction equation, Li<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup> + V<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> + e<ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> → Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">In step 3, we need to build weak oxidizing atmosphere to “kick out” Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf>, and Li<ce:inf loc="post">Zn</ce:inf> is stable under this condition. After several years' exploration, we have found that NO could achieve this process. The annealing equipment and results are shown in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0210" refid="fig8">Figures 8</ce:cross-ref>G–8I. Our current result shows that “kicking out” Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf> is difficult to achieve in single crystals, although it works well in homo-epitaxial thin films (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0215" refid="fig9">Figure 9</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="fig9"/>A). The reason for this could be that some dynamic factors have not been well investigated. Currently, the good result is exhibited in homogeneous epitaxy layers of Ga-doped ZnO. These epitaxy layers have achieved the transformation of p-type via the three-step thermodynamic process. A P-n junction is formed automatically between p-ZnO and substrate epitaxy, which exhibits good performance in rectification. After adding metal electrodes, each device based on this p-n junction has visible electroluminescence (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0220" refid="fig9">Figures 9</ce:cross-ref>B and 9C).</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec5" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0075">Conclusion and Outlook</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">In conclusion, we combine the knowledge of semiconductor physicists and materials scientists and present that the conduction type of a semiconductor is determined by CCCE. Based on this understanding, we have proposed a multi-step thermodynamic process for fabricating desired semiconductors. Through this strategy, we can realize ARCC by controlling the CCCE and satisfy the “boundary condition” of ALI as well. The entire article is illustrated by the example of ZnO:Li. In fact we believe that our strategy to realize ARCC is universal. In 2009, we achieved stable modulation of carrier concentration for n-ZnO with the highest mobility in ZnO:Al through this strategy.<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0225" refid="bib12">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">12</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">,</ce:sup>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0230" refid="bib13">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">13</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref> We believe that it should be easier to achieve ARCC in ionic compound semiconductors. Theoretically, by analyzing the connection among materials’ CCCE, carrier concentration, and the thermodynamic process, many “insulators” can be transformed into semiconductors. To illustrate our belief, we provide a brief introduction of our conjecture on the fabrication of p-GaN with high hole concentration in the same spirit of the multi-step thermodynamic process.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">As is known, ARCC for p-GaN doping has not been completely realized. Experimental results prove that GaN cannot possess high excitation efficiency with high concentration of Mg doping. This can be easily explained by the thermodynamic steady state of CCCE, i.e., the incorporation of large Mg amounts under a single thermodynamic condition always tends to form thermodynamically stable <mml:math altimg="si6.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>GaN</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>Mg</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>3</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>N</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, rather than unstable <mml:math altimg="si7.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>GaN</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>MgN</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, as shown in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0235" refid="fig10">Figure 10</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="fig10"/>A. This result is ultimately attributed to the fact that substitution of Mg (Mg<ce:inf loc="post">Ga</ce:inf>) always tends to be associated with interstitial Mg (Mg<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf>) of half Mg<ce:inf loc="post">Ga</ce:inf> content, making it difficult to increase the hole concentration. This case is exactly the same as that of doping Li in ZnO analyzed above.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">Our conjecture to fabricate p-GaN shares the same basic spirit as the proposed strategy to fabricate p-ZnO, but the specific method is different due to the difference in thermodynamic characteristics between GaN and ZnO. <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0240" refid="fig10">Figure 10</ce:cross-ref>B shows the multi-step thermodynamic process we propose to fabricate p-GaN. As the vapor pressure of Ga is too small, V<ce:inf loc="post">Ga</ce:inf> is difficult to create. We suggest to dope Mg directly under a particular condition and introduce Li at the same time, which is expected to form <mml:math altimg="si8.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>GaN</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>Mg</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>N</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>Li</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, rather than <mml:math altimg="si6.gif">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>GaN</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>Mg</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>3</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mtext>N</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>δ</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>. By adjusting the thermodynamic condition, it is then possible to enable most of large-radius Mg to fill in the Ga substitution and most of small-radius Li fill in the interstitial sites. On this basis, if we can find another thermodynamic condition to “kick out” small-radius Li<ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf>, ideally it is possible to achieve the result that most Mg is in the form of Mg<ce:inf loc="post">Ga</ce:inf>, and thus to achieve high acceptor excitation efficiency of GaN.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">Our strategy of a multi-step thermodynamic process with more attention paid to ALI holds great potential to be effective in many ionic compounds generally considered as insulators. Therefore, we believe that this strategy has a universal significance for achieving TIS in more materials.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
