                  <ce:bib-reference id="bib1">
                     <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                     <ce:note>
                        <ce:simple-para id="rspara0010" view="all">The term “doping” in semiconductor physics actually means the introduction of all nonperiodic factors, including the element substitution, vacancy formation, and behavior of homogeneous and heterogeneous atoms entering the interstitial site of lattice. Purity doping is not the only factor material scientists consider. Take Si for example. If one P atom replaces a Si atom in the lattice, the periodic structure of Si is destroyed—a well-recognized doping in semiconductor physics and materials science; however, if one Si atom is removed from the complete lattice, the periodic structure of Si is also destroyed, but this is not recognized as doping in materials science.</ce:simple-para>
                     </ce:note>
                  </ce:bib-reference>
                  <ce:bib-reference id="bib2">
                     <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                     <ce:note>
                        <ce:simple-para id="rspara0015" view="all">The arbitrary regulation of carrier concentration refers to the precise control of carrier concentration at any desired spatial location of semiconductor materials. Only with this precise control can it be possible to design the built-in electric field for various semiconductors.</ce:simple-para>
                     </ce:note>
                  </ce:bib-reference>
                  <ce:bib-reference id="bib3">
                     <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                     <ce:note>
                        <ce:simple-para id="rspara0020" view="all">The reason why ARCC can be achieved easily in Si can be described as follows. First, Si has a diamond-stabilized structure and most of the elemental impurities have no solid solubility in Si, which is easy to purify. What is more, the elements P and B have a doping solid solubility of 0.1%–4% in Si, which can dope in Si with fine control. It so happens that doping P in the position of Si forms a thermally stable shallow donor level, and doping B will form a thermally stable shallow acceptor level, which is relatively difficult to achieve for many materials.</ce:simple-para>
                     </ce:note>
                  </ce:bib-reference>
