                        <ce:simple-para id="rspara0025" view="all">There is a common typical feature in WBGSs, namely, it is easy to achieve one conduction type doping while it is difficult to achieve another conduction type doping, and the mechanism has not yet been clarified. For instance, in ZnO it is easy to achieve n-type doping, while stable p-type doping is very difficult; for diamond the opposite applies. In the 1970s, researchers explored the fabrication scheme of n-type GaN but were unable to find a favorable method to achieve stable p-type doping. It was partial realization of p-type GaN (whereby the carrier concentration of 10<ce:sup loc="post">19</ce:sup> cm<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup> was not well achieved) that led to the emergence of violet LED.</ce:simple-para>
