                  <ce:bib-reference id="bib9">
                     <ce:label>9</ce:label>
                     <ce:note>
                        <ce:simple-para id="rspara0030" view="all">The energy band theory shows that a complete periodic potential field will be formed in an integrated lattice, which theoretically will not be scattered and lose energy. The carrier exists in the form of a wave function in the periodic potential field. Once the lattice is unintegrated, the potential field is destroyed locally, which equates to a local potential barrier in quantum mechanics that will form a scattering center with cross-section. The larger the lattice deformation, the larger the barrier formed. A large scattering center with large cross-section results in a fatal effect on carrier mobility.</ce:simple-para>
                     </ce:note>
                  </ce:bib-reference>
                  <ce:bib-reference id="bib10">
                     <ce:label>10</ce:label>
                     <ce:note>
                        <ce:simple-para id="rspara0035" view="all">In many cases, especially that of variable valence, the value of <ce:italic>δ</ce:italic> can be a measurable one. For example, in the superconducting YBa<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>Cu<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>O(7−<ce:italic>δ</ce:italic>), <ce:italic>δ</ce:italic> can vary from 0 to 0.6.</ce:simple-para>
